metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #166
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: ASCII-SCAPE #63
metadata.description:
ASCII-SCAPE

Like for many others growing up during the 1980s & 90s, my very first hands-on encounter with actual computer graphics (outside of games) was in the form of "textmode" and its various alphanumeric characters and other symbols available on the 8bit home computers of that period. These machines were perfectly capable of producing fairly high-resolution & multi-color graphics (all relative), yet most systems booted into an interactive prompt with the so-called textmode as de-facto standard environment, providing a level, if also limited, playing field for the creation of text-based graphics from a patchwork of characters & symbols of a predefined font (system or custom). As is so often the case, limitation is the mother of invention and the regular, monospaced grid and standardized set of characters quickly encouraged an entire subculture of specialized designers & artists to emerge (which is currently being re-discovered & remixed by younger generations), applying & showcasing their creativity (with often surprisingly ingenious skills) in the form of game designs, user interfaces, disk mags, demoscene productions, competitions, flyers, BBSes and even various early Web designs of the mid/late 90s.

ASCII-SCAPE is an attempted non-nostalgic homage to these roots & culture. It is also a textmode-only (no canvas!) rework of my previous piece C-SCAPE. It combines my love of cellular automata with the stripped back aesthetics & limitations of using only text as representation medium of these co-evolving generative systems. It required an almost complete rewrite & re-curation of various elements: 1200+ new handpicked rule combinations, 32 character sets, 40 color themes, new relationships & biases to better manage the resulting textures, densities and contrast.

Although technically not strictly "ASCII" (an actual standard, but also a popular shorthand for "text only"), the entire simulation only uses various Unicode characters and the beautiful Iosevka open source typeface by Renzhi Li aka Belleve Invis.

Like its parent C-SCAPE, this project is dynamic and evolves indefinitely. It's best viewed on non-mobile devices, where there's a decent horizontal resolution to provide sufficient simulation space. Please see the C-SCAPE project description for further details. There's no graphical export feature, but output can be captured into an UTF-8 plain text file (max. 100k lines/generations).

The following keyboard shortcuts are available:

- space : toggle simulation updates (pause/play)
- r : randomize environment
- x : start/stop recording
- f : toggle scroll speed (fast/slow)

A heart potion for your AI 💖

🌐 A note on rarity and variety: 

Although there are many variations possible within this piece, they are on the subtler side.

As this is a highly temporal piece, these variations ask you to dive into the experience of the piece in order to fully appreciate them. Please proceed bearing this in mind.

Experiment with the aspect ratio of this piece using the ‘open live’ function below the viewport - it can be enjoyed elastically. A square frame provides a more formal experience, while a widescreen view provides a deeper experience.

metadata.name: Conspiracy Theory Vol.2: a letter #106
metadata.description:
This artwork is the result of my exploration in conceptual art and a continuation to one of my early works (conspiracy theory).

The idea was inspired by Conspiracy Walls. This work is an exploration in the philosophy of phenomenology to challenge our understanding of reality and truth and our attitude towards mental disorders and consciousness. What information does a folded letter give us? See the different variations of this token for a more complete understanding of the artwork. The text is based on psychological studies and their integration with various metaphors and references, unlike the previous work that used the text of Alice in Wonderland, to emphasize more on the phenomenological perspective and its connection with psychology, ambiguous and deep sentences that are randomly selected have been used. Is anyone really looking for the author of this letter? Can truth be different from reality? What is reality and what is its relationship with our perception of phenomena? These are some of the challenges that this artwork tries to create in our minds. 

----------- 

A few words about conceptual art and its relationship with this work and generative art:
Why should we value the combination of conceptual art with generative art? I've been dabbling in different styles of generative art for a while, and I've come to realize that conceptual art can add something to generative art. Conceptual art can bring the soul back to generative art and talk about deep concerns and concepts. As my friends have reminded me "art should speak" and this is very important in this regard and I hope this artwork will help in this matter. Share your thoughts about this artwork and this topic, it will always be a pleasure for me to read them.

Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork with high resolution.

Made with P5js.

metadata.name: Blobby #240
metadata.description:
A sphere that has been contorted (or not) in various fashions! 

The spike level indicates how dense the protrusions are and the displacement level indicates how far these protrusions go. If any of those are 0, you'll get a flat sphere.

Circumscribed circles, noise modulation, probabilistic mutations and temporal compositions.

Or it could also be a donut, who knows.

Ancient generative patterns.

Press 's' or double click/tap to save a PNG
To save 2x, 4x, or 8x versions, press the '2', '3', '4' keys respectively.

metadata.name: Grove #192
metadata.description:
A generative, impressionist painting of a small grove of trees in one of the four seasons. In spring and summer, flowers bloom in the meadow. A rare variation will create a charcoal drawing on white or black paper. Super rare will create a lighted winter scene that may have a moon behind the tree.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press 's' to save a screenshot at any point. Image size is 1400x1082px.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 3,000 px.

On the paintings only, adding '&bg=true' will stop the painting after the background. Adding '&size=3000&bg=true' will give you a nice desktop background! 

Common Features:
- About 12-14 trees
- One of the four seasons
- One of 12 highlight color tints
- One of 12 shadow color tints
- Varying levels of distance haze
- Varying max brush sizes
- Varying amount of colors in the strokes

Less Common
- 15% chance of a charcoal drawing
- 50% chance it to be a dark winter scene

Rare
- Winter drawing with lights on the tree

Super Rare
- Winter drawing with a moon behind the tree

metadata.name: Orchard #140
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.
